{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17441"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17441"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPopulation health studies have identified an interesting paradox where recent immigrants to developed countries often demonstrate better health outcomes compared to the local-born population, despite generally having lower socioeconomic status.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this epidemiological phenomenon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Healthy migrant effect","Cultural immunity advantage","Immigrant resilience syndrome","Demographic transition effect","Social gradient reversal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehealthy migrant effect\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-documented phenomenon where recent immigrants demonstrate better health outcomes than the host population, despite often facing socioeconomic disadvantages. This effect is attributed to several factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESelection bias - those who migrate tend to be younger and healthier\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECultural practices that may be protective against certain health conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELower rates of harmful behaviours like smoking or excessive alcohol consumption\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECultural immunity advantage\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a non-existent biological mechanism and incorrectly suggests that cultural factors provide immunity to disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmigrant resilience syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised term in epidemiology and mischaracterises the observed health advantage as a medical condition.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDemographic transition effect\u003C/strong\u003E describes the changes in birth and death rates as societies develop, which is unrelated to migrant health outcomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESocial gradient reversal\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised epidemiological term and fails to capture the temporary nature of the migrant health advantage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe healthy migrant effect typically diminishes over time as immigrants adopt local lifestyle habits and face barriers to healthcare access. This highlights the importance of maintaining equitable healthcare access for migrant populations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The healthy migrant effect describes how recent immigrants often have better health outcomes than the host population despite socioeconomic disadvantages.","This health advantage typically diminishes over time as immigrants adopt local lifestyle habits and face barriers to healthcare access.","Selection bias contributes to the healthy migrant effect as those who migrate tend to be younger and healthier."],"references":["Huang G, Guo F, Cheng Z, et al. Nativity in the healthy migrant effect: Evidence from Australia. SSM Popul Health. 2023;23:101457. Published 2023 Jun 22. doi:10.1016/j.ssmph.2023.101457","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17441"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:23:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:24:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://ap